.TH HASHTABLE 3 "2026-07-21" "libctools" "libctools Programmer's Manual"
.SH NAME
ht_create, ht_insert, ht_get, ht_remove, ht_destroy \- thread-unsafe O(1) key-value lookup table
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include <libctools.h>
.HP
.BI "hash_table_t *ht_create(size_t " initial_size ");"
.HP
.BI "bool ht_insert(hash_table_t *" ht ", const char *" key ", void *" value ");"
.HP
.BI "void *ht_get(hash_table_t *" ht ", const char *" key ");"
.HP
.BI "bool ht_remove(hash_table_t *" ht ", const char *" key ");"
.HP
.BI "void ht_destroy(hash_table_t *" ht ");"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The hashtable module provides dynamic, generic key-value storage using DJB2 hashing with linked-list chaining for collision handling.
.PP
.IP \(bu 3
.B Dynamic Resizing:
When the load factor exceeds 0.75 (\fIcount / size >= 0.75\fR), the table automatically doubles its bucket allocation and re-hashes existing nodes to preserve O(1) time complexity.
.IP \(bu 3
.B Key Memory Ownership:
Keys passed to
.BR ht_insert ()
are duplicated internally via
.BR malloc ()
and
.BR memcpy (),
guaranteeing safe string ownership.
.IP \(bu 3
.B Item Removal:
.BR ht_remove ()
unlinks and frees the internal key buffer and node memory associated with a given string key without disturbing adjacent nodes in the chain.
.SH RETURN VALUE
.BR ht_create ()
returns a pointer to the newly allocated table control block, or NULL on allocation failure or invalid size.
.PP
.BR ht_insert ()
and
.BR ht_remove ()
return true on success, or false on allocation failure or missing key.
.PP
.BR ht_get ()
returns a pointer to the stored value, or NULL if the key is not found.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR vector (3),
.BR string (3)